The paper focuses on optimizing the energy consumption of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for computer vision applications, which falls under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). The proposed method involves pruning the CNNs, which is a common technique in machine learning and falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves using energy consumption estimation to guide the pruning process, which involves optimization and falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves minimizing the error in output feature maps, which involves neural networks and falls under the category of neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper involves optimizing CNNs for battery-powered mobile devices, which involves embedded systems and falls under the category of computer architecture (cs.AR).
